name: 2,4-Dinitro-N-phenylaniline
Reason: The compound 2,4-Dinitro-N-phenylaniline has several functional groups that will influence its melting point. Firstly, the basic unit aniline has a melting point of around -6°C due to its aromatic ring and amine group, which engage in hydrogen bonding. Each nitro group contributes significantly to an increase in the melting point because they are strong electron-withdrawing groups, improving intermolecular forces such as dipole-dipole interactions and possibly hydrogen bonding; a single nitro group can add roughly +80°C to the melting point of an aromatic compound. Additionally, the extra phenyl group also increases the melting point due to providing added molecular weight and Van der Waals forces, contributing about +20°C. The overall effect is cumulative, with three functional groups (one amine, two nitro) present on an aromatic system. The melting point is predicted by adding the contributions from each functional group to the base melting point of aniline.
Prediction: Starting from a base value of -6°C for aniline, adding +160°C for the two nitro groups (2 x +80°C), and +20°C for the extra phenyl group, the predicted melting point would be -6°C + 160°C + 20°C = 174°C.
